"script": "Your grandmother's cast iron pan was once a river of fire. You see, chunks of scrap iron are dropped into a furnace and heated past 2,000 degrees until they melt completely. Then this glowing orange liquid is poured into a sand mold shaped exactly like a pan. And here's the clever part: that sand can be smashed apart and reused again and again. Next, the cooled pan is blasted clean and rubbed with oil baked onto its surface. Finally, that oil hardens into a natural nonstick coating, which is exactly why old pans only get better with age.",
